text: We have not heard of one police officer dying from Covid-19 across the world.
label: Incorrect. Many Covid-19 deaths among police officers have been reported worldwide, including at least one such death in the UK.

text: A post claims that the 1918 influenza bout had a deadly second wave after quarantine restrictions were lifted.
label: It is true the second wave of the pandemic was the most deadly, but it did not happen due to lifting of quarantine.

text: The survival rate for Covid-19 is 98.54% in the UK.
label: We don’t know what the survival rate is yet, as we don’t know how many people have had the disease. This figure comes from a claim about the US which is a slight over-estimate based on available figures.

text: The Covid-19 vaccines are experimental.
label: All the Covid-19 vaccines being used in the UK have been safety tested and approved for use by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency.

text: The vaccine manufacturers do not have liability.
label: Covid-19 vaccine manufacturers are immune to some, but not all, civil liability.

text: Covid-19 has a survival rate of 99.8%.
label: The survival rate varies by country but this estimate is too high for the UK. Estimates of the survival rate range from around 99% to 99.5%.

text: This means in the UK the Covid-19 survival rate for 0-59 year olds is 99.991%.
label: It doesn’t mean this. The data used only talks about England, and we can’t know for sure how many 0-59 year olds in England have had and recovered from Covid-19.

text: According to NHS data, as of 21st January there have been 4,717 Covid-19 deaths of people between the ages of 0-59 in the UK.
label: This is not true. The NHS data used in this video is just for England, not the whole UK, and only includes hospital deaths after a positive test.

text: 4,717 Covid-19 deaths out of the 0-59 year-old UK population means a 0.009% fatality rate.
label: This is wrong on a few levels. The death data is for England alone, and only for those dying in hospital after a positive test, and this calculation only works if every single person aged 0-59 has been infected with Covid.

text: The death rate in 2020 was lower than in the early 2000s.
label: This is correct. The death rate fell considerably over the past two decades, as life expectancy improved. 2020 saw these improvements reversed.

text: 2020 has had the 6th highest death rate in the past thirty years.
label: 2020 had the joint-11th highest death rate over the past three decades.

text: Fewer people have died from Covid-19 in the past 40 days than one day of cancer deaths.
label: The data used when the claim was made actually shows the number of people over a 40 day period who died of Covid-19 was higher than the average daily cancer death rate.

title: Face masks: protection or inadvertent harm? – Dubawa
text: A Facebook post seems to build on a claim made by a doctor in this Vanguard publication. The claim appears to point out that: Breathing over and over exhaled air turns into carbon dioxide, which is why we feel dizzy. Some people drive their car with the mask on; that is very dangerous because the stale air can make the driver lose consciousness. It is recommended to use face masks only if you have someone in front or very close, and it is essential to remember to lift it every 10 minutes to continue feeling healthy.
label: MISLEADING While face masks give us protection, they are not the most comfortable apparel as they are still not part of our noses! However, health authorities see them as necessary in the context of a pandemic. And the ones recommended for the public certainly don't make breathing difficult to the extent of rending the user dizzy. Further, we established that intermittent (every 10 minutes) lifting of one's cover is counterproductive; it is a sure means of infection, not protection. And, as for using a mask in a car, it's unnecessary if you are by your lonesome; it becomes imperative, however, if you have company. In truth, whatever discomfort wearing a face mask in public during a pandemic may cause is worth the trouble and only a small price to pay for good health.

title: “Infected Masks” WhatsApp Message, a Mixed Bag of Conjecture ...
text: China supplied 2 million masks to Africa; WHO says Africa must (should) prepare for the worst; China plans to distribute "infected" masks.
label: While parts of the chain message are true, the author distorted the context. Findings show that in total, over 6 million masks have been shipped to several countries in Africa. And while there are reports of some returned medical-masks, it was because they were defective, not infected. Further, the author took out of context, the WHO Director-General, Chief Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus’ cautionary message; although factual, his advisory was not to bolster the need to reject “infected shipped masks” from China. He instead, implored the health care systems in African countries against the imminent pandemic.

title: Is Sobolo the magic cure for coronavirus? – Dubawa Ghana
text: Let’s use traditional medicine to cure COVID-19 because China used just 'SOBOLO' to cure theirs
label: The claim is misleading. The hibiscus flower has not been proven or approved as a singular cure for the coronavirus and China has not ‘cured’ the virus by using the plant. The articles cited in the viral video did not name hibiscus (sobolo) as a coronavirus cure. Besides, no specific treatment has been identified as cure for COVID-19. Indeed, alternative medicine is being used by countries like China in their fight against the virus and may be a useful venture for other countries to follow. According to information from China, TCM is proving successful in COVID-19 treatment. However, these TCMs are being subjected to clinical trials and outcomes are being awaited. Furthermore, WHO, the organisation at the forefront of information regarding the pandemic, has not recommended any specific medicines to treat or cure COVID-19.

label: Falso

title: #Verificamos: É falso que quem consegue prender a respiração por ...
text: CONSELHOS EXCELENTES SÉRIOS por médicos japoneses que tratam casos de COVID-19. Todos devem garantir que sua boca e garganta estejam úmidas, nunca SECA. Tome alguns goles de água a cada 15 minutos, pelo menos. PORQUE? Mesmo que o vírus entre em sua boca ... beber água ou outros líquidos os lavará pelo esôfago e pelo estômago. Uma vez lá na barriga ... seu ácido do estômago matará todo o vírus. Se você não beber água suficiente com mais regularidade ... o vírus pode entrar nas traquéias e nos PULMÕES. Isso é muito perigoso
label: Falso

title: Beber água e fazer gargarejos com sal ou vinagre não impedem ...
text: O coronavírus antes de atingir os pulmões, permanece na garganta por quatro dias e, nesse período, a pessoa começa a tossir e sentir dores na garganta. Se essa pessoa beber muita água e faz gargarejo com água morna, sal ou vinagre, isso eliminará o vírus. Divulgue estas informações, pois você pode salvar alguém se essa pessoa souber disso.
label: falso

label: False

text: A book published in 1981 said that in 2020 a severe pneumonia-like illness would spread across the world, and calling it “Wuhan-400”.
label: These lines are from two different books: one is from a book of predictions by a psychic published in 2008 that predicted a pneumonia-like illness, and “Wuhan-400” is a fictional disease from a sci-fi book published in 1981 that bears little similarity to the new Wuhan coronavirus.

text: Two authors predicted the coronavirus decades before the outbreak.
label: A 1980s sci-fi novel describes a disease called “Wuhan-400” that bears little similarity to the new Wuhan coronavirus. A book of “prophecies about the end of the world” written in 2008 predicted that a pneumonia-like illness would spread across the world in the year 2020.

text: Each side of protective surgical masks has different functions, indicated by colour, and you should choose the way you wear by whether you are ill or not.
label: This is incorrect. Generally, if they have a coloured side, you should wear your mask with this pointing outward—but always read the manufacturer’s instructions to be sure.

text: Fibres from face masks and test swabs can cause Morgellons disease.
label: False. There is nothing sinister about these fibres and there is some debate as to whether Morgellons is a real disease.

text: Fibres from face masks and test swabs are evidence that nanoparticles are being inserted into us.
label: This is not true. Nanoparticles are not part of masks and swabs, and are too small to be seen with the naked eye.

text: Fibres from face masks and test swabs are evidence of parasites.
label: This is not true. There is nothing sinister about these fibres.

text: The masks they give to hospital staff and in schools say they do not protect against Covid-19.
label: The masks pictured may offer some limited protection to the wearer, and can stop them spreading it if they are infected. Hospital staff are required to wear these masks, but they may also wear respirators that do protect the wearer. Face coverings and masks are not recommended for use at schools in England except in some circumstances.

text: There is no reduction in viral transmission with the use of face masks.
label: Face masks can help to reduce transmission of SARS-Cov-2, and are recommended in many scenarios by the WHO and the UK government.

text: Asymptomatic carriers of Covid do not spread disease.
label: This isn’t true. As the pandemic has gone on, it has become clear that asymptomatic transmission can occur.

text: Face masks can cause low oxygen levels in the body.
label: The WHO has explicitly said that surgical masks do not cause low oxygen levels.

text: A police bulletin warns scammers are going door to door handing out face masks doused in chemicals that cause the wearer to fall unconscious, allowing them to rob the property.
label: There is no evidence of this police warning or of this crime taking place. This claim has been debunked around the world.

text: A peer-reviewed paper from Stanford University shows face masks don’t work.
label: The paper isn’t from Stanford and is strewn with basic errors.

text: Magnets can stick to your arm after a Covid-19 jab because they contain a microchip or other metals.
label: This is false. The vaccines do not contain a microchip and there is nothing in a vaccine that could cause a magnet to stick to your skin after getting it.

text: Covid-19 vaccines have caused 172 miscarriages since January 2021.
label: Miscarriages have been reported following vaccination, but there’s no evidence to show vaccines were the cause. The number of miscarriages reported after vaccination does not appear to exceed the number you would ordinarily expect.

text: Covid-19 barely mutated before vaccines were rolled out.
label: This is untrue. All four variants of concern, designated as such by the World Health Organisation, were identified before mass public vaccination programmes began.

text: The Covid-19 vaccines offer very little protection against the disease.
label: This is not true. The claim is based on a misinterpretation of a Lancet comment article, which compared different ways of measuring effectiveness. It did not refute the headline figures that have already been reported.

text: Lockdowns never slow transmission.
label: False. They do slow transmission.

text: Masks don’t work.
label: False. Masks do work to reduce viral transmission.

text: The vaccines are inadequately tested and somewhat dangerous.
label: False. The Covid-19 vaccines are tested thoroughly like any other vaccine and are safe.

text: PHE released a report revealing 62% of Covid-19 deaths are people who have been vaccinated.
label: PHE’s report suggests 61% of Covid-19 deaths with the Delta variant are in people who have received at least one vaccine dose. But this is not unexpected when no vaccine is 100% effective and so many vulnerable people have been vaccinated.

text: A vaccine for the coronavirus was being trialled in January 2020 days before the outbreak.
label: Incorrect. The trial referenced was for a different type of coronavirus—Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS).

text: The spike protein generated by a Covid-19 vaccine can leave the site of injection and enter the bloodstream, which could possibly be causing deaths and vaccine injuries.
label: There is some evidence that the spike proteins generated by the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine leave the site of injection. There is also evidence that the spike protein on the actual virus can damage cells that line blood vessels.  However, the two different spike proteins behave very differently in the body, and so the assumption that spike proteins generated by the vaccine could also harm cells in the bloodstream is unevidenced.

title: Saudi MERS vaccine study is not related to 2020 coronavirus outbreak
text: A post seeks to link a Saudi Arabian MERS vaccine study to the current coronavirus outbreak that originated in Wuhan, China.
publisher: AAP FactCheck Archives - Australian Associated Press
label: False - Based on the evidence, AAP FactCheck found the Facebook post to be false. The Saudi clinical trial is investigating a vaccine for the MERS Coronavirus strain, not the 2019 Novel Coronavirus.
